---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import PageHero from "../../components/page/PageHero.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Authenticity | Virtual Ventures"
  description="Human-made pattern and AI support statement for Virtual Ventures crochet patterns, photos and official verification."
  showFooterBreadcrumbs={false}
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Human Made"
    title="Authenticity"
    description="How Virtual Ventures uses real yarn, real notes, real photos and careful AI support without faking pattern results."
  />

  <main class="page-shell">
    <section class="page-intro">
      <p class="eyebrow">Authenticity</p>
      <h1>Real yarn, real hands</h1>
      <p>
        Virtual Ventures is built around human-made crochet patterns, practical
        testing, honest notes and official source links.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section content-left">
      <article class="content-card">
        <h2>Human-made patterns</h2>
        <p>
          Virtual Ventures crochet patterns are created by a real person using
          real yarn, hooks, notes, photos, testing, frogging, fixing and learning
          along the way.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finished examples should be real finished items, not fake product
          photos or fake customer results.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section content-right">
      <article class="content-card">
        <h2>How AI may help</h2>
        <p>
          AI may be used for spelling help, wording suggestions, layout support,
          organisation, accessibility wording, admin tasks and editing support.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI should not be described as generating the crochet pattern itself,
          fake finished objects, fake stitch photos, fake product photos or fake
          customer results.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section content-left">
      <article class="content-card">
        <h2>The official source</h2>
        <p>
          The Virtual Ventures website should be the official source for pattern
          IDs, version updates, corrections, QR code destinations, copyright
          notes and verification pages.
        </p>
        <p>
          If a marketplace listing, download or social post looks confusing,
          check the official Virtual Ventures page first.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section content-right">
      <article class="content-card">
        <h2>Pattern IDs and QR codes</h2>
        <p>
          Patterns may include a pattern ID, version number and QR code. These
          help readers find stitch help videos, livestream replays, updates,
          correction notes, policy pages and official verification.
        </p>
        <p>
          If a QR code or verification link does not lead to Virtual Ventures,
          treat it carefully and check the pattern on the official website.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-closing-card">
      <p>
        The goal is simple: make useful patterns people can trust without hiding
        where they came from.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
